[3] Wisconsin (Wood County)
Date: Fri 20 Dec 2013
Source: WSAU [edited]
http://wsau.com/news/articles/2013/dec/20/health-officials-seeing-more-pertussis-cases-in-central-wisconsin/


Local health officials are continuing to see a number of cases of pertussis, or whooping cough. The Wood County Health Department is still seeing infections. Public health nurse Diane Rodd says they've had 31 cases of pertussis so far in 2013. "Approximately 24 out of those 31 have occurred since 1 Nov 2013. So we are seeing an increase."

Rodd says many of the people being infected are students who are nearly out of date with their shots. "Because of that, the protection they got in kindergarten is starting to wane, and so they're a little more susceptible." The early symptoms are much like catching a cold, but the mild cough progressively worsens to severe coughing spells. These coughing spells can include whooping and vomiting. Health officials say the illness can last nearly 6 weeks, and is contagious if left untreated. A course of antibiotics is available to help lessen the length of the disease, and Rodd says they need to do their job. "We want to make sure people go through the entire cycle of antibiotics before going out into the public."

[Byline: Raymond Neupert]

