[5] Colorado (Phillips County)
Date: Fri 6 Dec 2013
Source: Fort Morgan (CO) Times [edited]
http://www.fortmorgantimes.com/fort-morgan-local-news/ci_24669544/pertussis-infections-rise-northeast-colorado


Over the past month the Northeast Colorado Health Department [NCHD] has received notification of 14 positive cases of pertussis, also known as whooping cough, in Phillips County, according to a recent press release.

The majority of the positive cases are in school-aged children and even though the cases are concentrated in Phillips County at this time, case rates are high across the state. Health officials are urging individuals that have a cough, or have a family member that has a cough, that has lasted more than 14 days to see their healthcare provider, and to make sure family member vaccinations are up to date.

"Pertussis has been circulating at epidemic levels in Colorado for the past couple of years so it's not surprising we're seeing increased cases in our area," said Dr Tony Cappello, NCHD's public health director, in the release. "While this infection can just be a nagging cough for some people, it can be very severe and even deadly for infants and others with compromised immune systems. This is not an illness you want to pass on to an infant that doesn't have the immunity to fight it off; whether it be your own grandchild, a neighbor's new baby, or your own newborn.

"It can also be very hard to get rid of once it gets in a community," continued Dr Cappello. "Over the course of our case investigations in Phillips County we've had to touch base with several other school districts alerting them to probable exposures at school events. The best thing that people can do if they think they have pertussis is to visit their healthcare provider, stay home if they're ill, cover their cough, stay away from infants, wash their hands, and make sure they're up to date on vaccinations."

